<br>
I feel that many of you (not Gromm nor Karadin) need to stop looking at the small picture so much, and give some of the larger guilds the benefit of a doubt.  Everyone assumes that everything the large guild's do is for their own good, when in reality it usually harms them (gives them less time to accomplish forward tasks by returning to ancient rotations that they have some loot stake in).<br>
<br>
Many times representatives of the larger guilds go about their arguments in the wrong way by implying that they can just perma-kill mobs if they want to.  The implied threat is not constructive, but allow me to illustrate something:  How would *I* know if AD loot was upgrades of people in BotS, if they didn't specifically allow me access to the loot records of all of their members.  BotS could have continued to kill AD for months under the guise of harvesting upgrade loot, and no one would no the difference.  It *could* have been for alts on the raid for all we know.  The fact that they moved on and DID NOT cockblock, shows that they are interested in sharing content.  Like I said above, a little more 'benefit of the doubt' here please.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>There is one thing that people seem to forget after every few pages of this thread.  The thing that everyone is forgetting repeatedly is that AD is not *currently* a rotation mob.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Notice, Gromm, that I did not say that he is not a *candidate* for rotation, something that we have talked about at length in private.<br>
<br>
It is important to note though, that since none of the guilds who have killed AD have *asked* for him to be put on rotation, teaming is perfectly acceptable up to the point at which they do.<br>
<br>
I am also supportive of the idea that no guild should have him put on rotation for the express purpose of cockblocking other guilds.  BotS, Tindi, and NB were kind enough to NOT cockblock the content from the rest of us, and I believe that guilds who kill AD in the future should remember this as a courtesy to those who came before them.<br>
<br>
However, if a guild, say ED were to begin to kill AD as a single entity, I feel that they (as well as many other guilds) would be interested in AD's loot as upgrades (unless of course the risk vs reward thing came up), and thus would be right in asking for him to be put on a rotation.  When this is done by a guild in that position, it will not be out of greed or any other rediculous notion.  It will be because this guild wants the chance to obtain loot from a mob as many times as possible without encroaching on the needs of other guilds at the same time.  Something that is seen in every rotation that is currently established.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
