<br>
Here is where you are going astray...  Rotations do penalize guilds who are mobile and strong.  If there were no rotations, some guild would be able to get a good lion's share of some mob, say Trakanon.  Say they can get 1/2 of all the spawn.  However, with 12 guilds on Trakanon rotation, the stronger guild can only get 1/12 of the spawns.  That is a penalty compared to what they are capable of.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How many rotations do we have now that we allow a guild to populate two rotation spots ON THE SAME ROTATION MOB in any form or fashion? Do we, at this time, have any rotation in existence that has GuildA on the rotation as a single entity ...and then has GuildA on the same rotation as an alliance entity?<br>
<br>
Zero you say? Did I hear Zero? Maybe you can explain to me how in the world allowing teamable rotations (something we legally allow now by the way from that complete waste of good internet bandwidth you call an Alliance Rule) would cause the situation you described above<br>
<br>
Or, were you talking about creating the following?:<br>
<br>
Mob #1 - GuildA, GuildB, GuildC<br>
Mob #2 - GuildB, GuildA + GuildC<br>
Mob #3 - GuildC, GuildB + GuildA<br>
<br>
I see no problem with this situation. GuildA = 2 rots (1 rot + 2 x .5 rot). GuildB = 2.5 rots (2 x 1 rot + .5 rot). GuildC = 2.5 rots (2 x 1 rot + .5 rot). GuildA is getting penalized for sharing two rots, GuildB and GuildC are only sharing one each. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
So, let's look at this closely.  The situation you describe *could* exist, but it is contrived.  A more realistic example would be:<br>
<br>
Mob #1 - GuildA, GuildB, GuildC<br>
Mob #2 - GuildA, GuildB, GuildC<br>
Mob #3 - GuildA, GuildB + GuildC<br>
<br>
I haven't ever seen any example that would be similar to what you have described, although you can imagine it happening... maybe.<br>
<br>
So, you have<br>
GuildA - 1/3 Mob #1, 1/3 Mob #2, 1/2 Mob #3<br>
GuildB - 1/3 Mob #1, 1/3 Mob #2, 1/4 Mob #3<br>
GuildC - 1/3 Mob #1, 1/3 Mob #2, 1/4 Mob #3<br>
<br>
A couple of things here.  Allowing this (I think this is exactly an example of what has been discussed) first enables GuildB and GuildC together to get 2/3 of Mob #1, 2/3 of Mob #2, and 1/2 of Mob #3 spawns.  The Mob #3 spawns are achievable *only* because of the alliance.  Otherwise it would be<br>
<br>
GuildA - 1/1 Mob #3<br>
GuildB - 0/1 Mob #3<br>
GuildC - 0/1 Mob #3<br>
<br>
If this were allowed, it is a very clear message that any guild who is capable of killing Mob #3 alone.  The message is this: In order to maximize the loot you get for your guild, you should divide your guild into N smaller guilds, each one capable of killing Mob #1 and Mob #2 individually, but team up on Mob #3.  Suppose GuildA splits into three &quot;subguilds&quot; - GuildA1, GuildA2, GuildA3 - for the sole purpose of maximizing loot intake.  The picture becomes:<br>
<br>
Mob #1 - GuildA1, GuildA2, GuildA3, GuildB, GuildC<br>
Mob #2 - GuildA1, GuildA2, GuildA3, GuildB, GuildC<br>
Mob #3 - GuildA(1+2+3), GuildB + GuildC<br>
<br>
That gives<br>
GuildA - 3/5 Mob #1, 3/5 Mob #2, 1/2 Mob #3<br>
GuildB - 1/5 Mob #1, 1/5 Mob #2, 1/4 Mob #3<br>
GuildC - 1/5 Mob #1, 1/5 Mob #2, 1/4 Mob #3<br>
<br>
So, in order to maximize loot intake for my guild, we should split up and each enter the rotations we want and team for the stuff we really want.  The alliance rules exist exactly to prevent this from happening.  If you want an alliance, it is because you want to ally to do achieve something you could not without the alliance, not because you want to maximize loot for your guild.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Once again, no matter how you slice it. One rotation entry = 2 loots. If one rotation entry is shared by two guilds, they are taking a 50% penalty for that rotation PER GUILD ...as opposed to no penalty for a guild that has a rotation entry to themselves.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, you assume that each guild can get the loot alone - if that was the case, they would do it alone to maximize loot intake.  Compare Mob #1 and Mob #3 above.  There is no logical reason to team up on a mob that you can kill alone.  You can't each kill it alone.  Going at it alone you get no loots each.  You team upso you can kill the mob as a team.  If you team up, you get the 1 loot each.  You can't do it alone so you team up to do it... Zero... vs. Two...  Alone you can't kill the mob = 0 loots... vs. teaming up you can kill the mob = 2 loots...  Alone, the mob kills you = 0 loots.... vs teaming up you kill the mob = 2 loots...  Alone = 0... vs. Team = 2...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'd like you to go and solo AD since it's all just tactics and nothing to do with numbers.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It does have something to do with numbers and something to do with tactics.  BotS has killed everything in PoP at or below Xegony level with 56 or fewer people lately, including a 46 person clearing of everything in PoFire except Fennin Ro and a 50 person killing of Rallos Zek The Warlord.  I'm not trying to brag, just showing you that some folks may require more numbers for whatever reasons.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...and once again, how many people did your guild take when they first killed Aerin'Dar, for example?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From our (BotS) DKP web page:<br>
<br>
Date                #Attendees        Items bought                Comments<br>
--------        --------        --------                ---------<br>
11/01/02        52                 0                         First Kill <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What we have now is some kind of evil, red-headed, hunch-backed step-child kind of rotation that ...while good in principal, lacks more than a bit of being fair to all people on The Rathe. It clearly favors larger guilds in progression through game content and is controlled by high end players who somehow believe that their game experience should be followed identically by all other guild entities on this server ...and they aren't afraid to use the RTA (a representative democratic organization? ...stay tuned, we don't really know yet) to force the will of the powerful onto the will of the less than powerful.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
